Crate root for `ctx-context`, the read-side of the CTX context system: computes and prints the rollup/intent summary chain above a given path, and provides a Claude Code hook that injects that chain into a session.

The file itself is just module declarations plus a doc comment establishing the architecture; no logic lives here. Key architectural fact stated in the doc comment: agents edit source directly with native tools now (post "lead-by-hooks pivot") — this crate is read-only tooling, not a write-side context manager. `serve`, `session`, and `hook` are described as pure over the `env::Env` boundary, meaning they take an `Env` abstraction rather than touching argv/filesystem/network directly; if editing those modules, preserve that boundary rather than reaching for `std::env` or `std::process` directly.

The binary entrypoint (elsewhere) is a thin wrapper over `cli::dispatch`, so CLI parsing/dispatch logic belongs in `cli`, not in `main`. Module list: `chain` (builds the summary chain), `cli` (argv dispatch), `env` (the `Env` abstraction), `error`, `freshness` (staleness checks against the hash tree implied by the wider CTX system), `hook` (Claude Code injection), `repo_path`, `serve` (prints the chain), `session`.